#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:36
msgid ""
"To start writing a shell script, it is convenient to use a text editor that "
"supports syntax highlighting."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:38
msgid "`vim`, for example, is a good tool for this."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:40
msgid "The name of the script should respect some rules:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:44
msgid "no names of existing commands;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:44
msgid "only alphanumeric characters, i.e. no accented characters or spaces;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:44
msgid "extension .sh to indicate that it is a shell script."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:46
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:77
msgid "!!! note"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:48
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The author uses the \"$\" throughout these lessons to indicate the user's command-prompt.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#!/usr/bin/env bash\n"
"#\n"
"# Author : Rocky Documentation Team\n"
"# Date: March 2022\n"
"# Version 1.0.0: Displays the text \"Hello world!\"\n"
"#\n"
"\n"
"# Displays a text on the screen :\n"
"echo \"Hello world!\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:62
msgid "To be able to run this script, as an argument to bash:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:63
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ bash hello-world.sh\n"
"Hello world !\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:69
msgid "Or, more simply, after having given it the right to execute:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:70
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ chmod u+x ./hello-world.sh\n"
"$ ./hello-world.sh\n"
"Hello world !\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:80
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    To execute the script, it needs to be called with `./` before its name when you are in the directory where the script resides. If not in that directory, you will need to call it with the entire path to the script, OR place it in a directory that is within your PATH environment variable: (Examples: `/usr/local/sbin`, `/usr/local/bin`, etc.)\n"
"    The interpreter will refuse to execute a script present in the current directory without indicating a path (here with `./` before it).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:82
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `chmod` command is to be passed only once on a newly created script.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:85
msgid ""
"The first line to be written in any script is to indicate the name of the "
"shell binary to be used to execute it.  If you want to use the `ksh` shell "
"or the interpreted language `python`, you would replace the line:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:86
#, no-wrap
msgid "#!/usr/bin/env bash\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:91
msgid "with :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "#!/usr/bin/env ksh\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:97
msgid "or with :"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:98
#, no-wrap
msgid "#!/usr/bin/env python\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:104
msgid ""
"This first line is called the `shebang`.  It starts with the characters `#!` "
"followed by the path to the binary of the command interpreter to use."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:106
msgid "!!! hint \"About the shebang\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:108
#, no-wrap
msgid "    You may have encountered the \"shebang\" in a script that you've looked at that does not contain the \"env\" section and simply contains the interpreter to use. (Example: `#!/bin/bash`). The author's method is considered to be the recommended and proper way to format the \"shebang\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:110
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Why is the author's method recommended? Because it increases the portability of the script. If for some reason the interpreter lived in an entirely different directory, the interpreter would **still** be found if you used the author's method.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:112
msgid ""
"Throughout the writing process, you should think about proofreading the "
"script, using comments in particular:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:115
msgid ""
"a general presentation, at the beginning, to indicate the purpose of the "
"script, its author, its version, its use, etc."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:115
msgid "during the text to help understand the actions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:117
msgid ""
"Comments can be placed on a separate line or at the end of a line containing "
"a command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:119
msgid "Example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/01-first-script.md:120
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# This program displays the date\n"
"date # This line is the line that displays the date!\n"
msgstr ""
